                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Headley quiz
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, March 26: Union home ministry officials said an Indian magistrate would be employed to record David Headleys statement as and when India gets direct access to interrogate the 26/11 terror suspect in the US.         
	India will send a request to US authorities for access to Headley. A team comprising National Investigation Agency (NIA) officials, Mumbai police officers, lawyers and a magistrate has been formed to interrogate him.        
	India hopes to record Headleys statement under the CrPCs Section 164, which will be admissible in an Indian court. A senior home ministry official said more than two Pakistan Army officers could be involved in the 26/11 plotting.                                                                                                                                                           
